{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, the term *naqsh* (often compounded as *naqsh-e-qadam*, *naqsh-e-paa*, or *naqsh-e-wafa*) carries rich metaphorical layers, primarily evoking a **trace, footprint, or imprint** left by the beloved—symbolizing longing, absence, fidelity's fleeting mark, or the indelible yet ephemeral evidence of love.[^1][^2] It also extends to **artistic design, painting, or scripted image**, portraying the world as a canvas of divine or lover's creation, fraught with complaint, illusion, and coquetry.[^3][^4]\n\nThis duality underscores Ghalib's philosophical irony: the lover discerns paradise (or ruin) in the beloved's passing step, yet the \"painted world\" (*naqsh faryadi*) laments its own scripted beauty as a petitioner's plea. Such imagery blends Sufi ecstasy with existential lament, where *naqsh* marks both union's memory and separation's wound.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 90 (“Jahan tera naqsh-e-qadam dekhte hain”), [p-b88355](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/90/translation/#p-b88355): \"Wherever the trace of your footstep appears, we see, / In every garden path, a paradise we see.\"\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 90 (“Jahan tera naqsh-e-qadam dekhte hain”), [p-44744c](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/90/translation/#p-44744c): \"Find the trace of my lament's fire in this scarred heart; / It is the night-traveler's own footprint that we see.\"\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 29 (“Dehr mein naqsh-e-wafa wajah-e-tasalli na hua”), [p-cffc40](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/29/translation/#p-cffc40): \"For faith to bring the world a remedy, it was not to be.\" (*Naqsh-e-wafa* = trace/imprint of fidelity.)\n\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 153 (“Naqsh faryadi hai kis ki shokhi-e-tehreer ka”), [p-0e42b0](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/153/translation/#p-0e42b0): \"Whose playful script does this whole painted world complain of?\"\n\n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 154 (“Naqsh-e-naaz-e-but-e-tannaz be-aaghosh-e-raqeeb”), [p-aa2e44](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/154/translation/#p-aa2e44): \"That cruel beauty's artful pose...\"",
